optInternal.design:
CORE INTERFACE (packages/llm/src/types.ts), deliberately small:

```ts
// Normalized request — provider-agnostic
interface LlmRequest {
  model: string;                 // canonical id, e.g. "claude-sonnet-4", mapped per adapter
  system?: string;               // ALWAYS a top-level field; adapters place it correctly
  messages: LlmMessage[];        // role: 'user'|'assistant'|'tool'
  tools?: ToolDef[];             // JSON-Schema params, normalized
  toolChoice?: 'auto'|'none'|'required'|{ name: string };
  temperature?: number;
  maxTokens?: number;            // REQUIRED downstream for Anthropic; we default it
  stopSequences?: string[];
  signal?: AbortSignal;          // cancellation, works in Node + WebView fetch
  providerOptions?: Record<string, unknown>; // typed escape hatch (caching, reasoning, etc.)
}

interface LlmMessage {
  role: 'user' | 'assistant' | 'tool';
  content: ContentPart[];        // normalized parts, not raw strings
}
type ContentPart =
  | { type: 'text'; text: string }
  | { type: 'tool_call'; id: string; name: string; args: unknown }      // assistant -> wants tool
  | { type: 'tool_result'; toolCallId: string; result: unknown; isError?: boolean };

interface ToolDef {
  name: string;
  description?: string;
  parameters: JSONSchema7;       // single canonical schema; adapters reshape
}

// Normalized non-streaming result
interface LlmResult {
  content: ContentPart[];        // text + any tool_call parts
  stopReason: StopReason;
  usage: Usage;
  raw: unknown;                  // provider response, for debugging/escape hatch
}
type StopReason = 'stop' | 'length' | 'tool_use' | 'content_filter' | 'error';

interface Usage {
  inputTokens: number;
  outputTokens: number;
  cacheReadTokens?: number;      // Anthropic/DeepSeek expose; others undefined
  cacheWriteTokens?: number;
  costUsd?: number;              // computed by a pricing table keyed on canonical model id
}

// Normalized streaming — one discriminated union for ALL providers
type StreamChunk =
  | { type: 'text_delta'; text: string }
  | { type: 'tool_call_start'; id: string; name: string }
  | { type: 'tool_call_delta'; id: string; argsJsonDelta: string }  // partial JSON
  | { type: 'tool_call_end'; id: string }
  | { type: 'stop'; stopReason: StopReason; usage: Usage }
  | { type: 'error'; error: LlmError };

interface LlmProvider {
  readonly id: 'anthropic' | 'openai' | 'gemini' | 'deepseek';
  generate(req: LlmRequest, key: string): Promise<LlmResult>;
  stream(req: LlmRequest, key: string): AsyncIterable<StreamChunk>;
  supports: CapabilityFlags;     // { tools, streaming, parallelToolCalls, vision, promptCache, reasoning }
}
```

FALLBACK CHAINS live OUTSIDE the adapters, in a small `withFallback(providers: LlmProvider[])` runner in packages/core (or llm): try provider[0], on a classified-retryable LlmError (rate limit, 5xx, overload) move to next; surface per-attempt usage so cost accounting is accurate even on failover. Adapters stay dumb; the chain is policy. This keeps per-agent fallback (Anthropic -> OpenAI -> DeepSeek) a config concern, not adapter code.

WHAT MUST BE NORMALIZED (the actual work):
1. SYSTEM PROMPT PLACEMENT: OpenAI/DeepSeek -> a {role:'system'} message prepended. Anthropic -> top-level `system` param (NOT a message). Gemini -> `systemInstruction` field on the request. We keep `system` as one field and each adapter routes it.
2. TOOL/FUNCTION SCHEMA: OpenAI/DeepSeek -> `tools:[{type:'function',function:{name,description,parameters}}]`. Anthropic -> `tools:[{name,description,input_schema}]`. Gemini -> `tools:[{functionDeclarations:[{name,description,parameters}]}]` with a RESTRICTED OpenAPI-subset schema (no $ref, limited formats) — the riskiest reshape; we validate/strip unsupported JSON-Schema keywords for Gemini. One canonical JSONSchema7 in, three shapes out.
3. TOOL CALL / RESULT ROUND-TRIP: OpenAI -> assistant `tool_calls[]` with id + stringified JSON args; result is a {role:'tool',tool_call_id} message. Anthropic -> assistant `content` block `tool_use{id,name,input}`; result is a user message with `tool_result{tool_use_id}` block. Gemini -> `functionCall{name,args}` part; result is a `functionResponse` part (NO id — we synthesize/track ids ourselves by name+order). Normalizing the missing-id case for Gemini is a real edge.
4. STREAMING EVENTS: OpenAI/DeepSeek -> SSE `chat.completion.chunk` with `choices[].delta` (content or tool_calls fragments; tool-call args arrive as incremental JSON string fragments per index). Anthropic -> typed event stream: message_start, content_block_start/delta(text_delta|input_json_delta)/stop, message_delta(carries stop_reason+usage), message_stop. Gemini -> `streamGenerateContent` emitting candidate chunks with parts. Each adapter folds its native events into our StreamChunk union; tool-arg JSON deltas are concatenated into argsJsonDelta and parsed at tool_call_end.
5. STOP REASONS: OpenAI stop|length|tool_calls|content_filter -> our enum. Anthropic end_turn|max_tokens|tool_use|stop_sequence -> our enum. Gemini STOP|MAX_TOKENS|SAFETY|RECITATION -> our enum. We map to {stop,length,tool_use,content_filter,error}.
6. USAGE FIELDS: OpenAI usage{prompt_tokens,completion_tokens} (+prompt_tokens_details.cached_tokens). Anthropic usage{input_tokens,output_tokens,cache_read_input_tokens,cache_creation_input_tokens}. Gemini usageMetadata{promptTokenCount,candidatesTokenCount}. DeepSeek mirrors OpenAI + prompt_cache_hit_tokens. Critically: in STREAMING, OpenAI requires stream_options:{include_usage:true} to emit a final usage chunk; Anthropic puts usage in message_delta; Gemini in the final chunk. Cost is OUR pricing table keyed on canonical model id, not from the provider.

DEPENDENCY POSTURE: prefer official SDKs (@anthropic-ai/sdk, openai, @google/generative-ai) for typed event parsing and retry plumbing; DeepSeek uses the `openai` SDK with a custom baseURL (api.deepseek.com) — no separate dep. Alternatively, raw fetch + SSE parser to drop all deps (max no-lock-in) at the cost of re-implementing SSE/retry. Recommended middle path: SDKs behind the adapter boundary so they are swappable without touching callers.

optStrategy.design:
The seam is a single TypeScript interface in @relavium/llm, owned by Relavium, expressed only in Relavium/Zod types — never re-exporting any vendor type. Concretely:

  interface LLMProvider {
    readonly id: 'anthropic'|'openai'|'google'|'deepseek';
    stream(req: LLMRequest, signal: AbortSignal): AsyncIterable<LLMChunk>;
  }
  // LLMRequest: { model, messages: RelaviumMessage[], tools: CanonicalTool[], temperature?, maxTokens? }
  // LLMChunk (discriminated union): {type:'text', delta} | {type:'tool_call', id, name, argsDelta} | {type:'usage', input, output} | {type:'finish', reason}

The 4 providers map cleanly: Anthropic via @anthropic-ai/sdk (messages.stream); OpenAI, DeepSeek, and Gemini all via the OpenAI Chat Completions wire format (OpenAI SDK + base-URL swap — DeepSeek and Gemini both ship OpenAI-compatible endpoints), so in practice it's roughly TWO adapter shapes, not four. The existing docs already place ToolNormalizer (one canonical tool shape ↔ each provider's input_schema/function.parameters/functionDeclarations), FallbackChain (the agent.yaml ordered list), and CostTracker (tokens→micro-units) ON the Relavium side of the seam, so an implementation swap touches only the per-provider stream() body, not normalization/fallback/cost. AgentRunner consumes LLMChunk and re-emits the public RunEvent union (agent:token/agent:tool_call/node:completed.tokensUsed) — that union, not the provider response, is what every surface and Phase-2 SSE bind to. Provider selection is a factory keyed by the agent.yaml `provider` string (already a plain string in the Zod schema, not a vendor enum). Hosts: identical in Node worker (CLI/engine) and Tauri — both adapter styles are plain fetch/SDK over HTTPS with an injected key from the keychain and an AbortController; no browser-only or Node-only assumption crosses the seam (matches packages/core's "zero platform-specific imports").
